@c %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
@node CoreOptions, Configuration, Mixed, Top

@chapter CoreOptions

Several options control the way Cthugha displays the sound. In lack of a
better name I use CoreOption for those (I you know a better name, please
tell me about it).

As you already know Cthugha uses (multiple) buffers that are mapped to
the screen. So all the CoreOptions (except the one controlling how the
buffers are mapped to the screen) are defined for each buffer.

The CoreOptions are
@table @emph
@item Display
How the buffers are mapped to the screen

@item Flame
How the buffers change from one time step to the next. 

@item General Flame
A Parameter used by some flame.

@item Border
What values to use for the upper and lower border of the buffer.

@item Translate
Defines a global movement on the buffers

@item Wave
How the sound data is drawn into the buffer

@item Sound Processing
Some filters for the sound. 

@item Table
How the palette is used by some of the waves.

@item WaveScale
A parameter controlling the size of some the waves.

@item Palette
What colors to use for this buffer.

@item PCX
The next image that will be used (displayed sometimes). This feature is
not working very well.

@item Flashlight
Change the palette based on beats. 
@end table


You can lock each of these CoreOptions individually. You can do this
either when starting Cthugha for example with @code{--display lock:up}
or when Cthugha is running: Press @code{o} to the a list of the current
CoreOptions, select the one you would like to lock and press @code{l}.

You can use the function keys (starting from @code{F5}) to get lists of
the possible values of all the CoreOptions.


