@node Keymaps, Technical Stuff, Parameters, Top

@chapter Keymaps

Since version 1.4 of Cthugha-L you can define your own keyboard
bindings. 

@code{#keymap name} marks the beginning of a new keymap. 
There must be no white spaces after @code{name}.
Then the keybindings are of the form @code{key action1(param1) action2(param2) ...}.
Commenets start with an @code{#} at the beginning of the line.
For an example of a keymap file see @code{src/default.keymap}.

Key presses in Cthugha are handled by a series of keymaps. When one
keymap can not handle the key, it is passed on to the next general one.
The sequence of keymaps is depending on the current interface mode
@table @emph
@item main interface
extraKeymap (as defined by the @code{setExtraKeymap} action)@*
@code{main}@*
@code{default}

@item Options, CoreOptions, Sound, ...
@code{CoreOptionElement} (only for CoreOptions), @code{OptionElement}@*
@code{CoreOption} for CoreOptions
@code{Option} or @code{Sound}, ...@*
@code{default} 

@item Screen, Flame, ... Lists
@code{Option} for the yes/no value in each line, and to move the selection@*
@code{Screen} or @code{Flame}, ...@*
@code{List}@*
@code{default}

@end table

An example keymap, that lets you select the flames by just one keypress.
@example
#keymap main
# turn on new flame keys
f   setExtraKeymap(flame)


#keymap flame

# go back to normal mode
q   setExtraKeymap()

a   flame(0)
# or use the flame name:  flame(clear)
s   flame(1)
d   flame(2)
...
@end example

